2026-02-17 03:53:15,379 - EVENT from author: 'prompt_generate_agent'
  - TOKEN_USAGE: Prompt=86083, Gen=1393
  - TOOL_CALL: prompt_generate_tool({"project_main_folder_path": "/root/fix_build_agent/process/project/ntopng", "max_depth": 1, "config_folder_path": "/root/fix_build_agent/oss-fuzz/projects/ntopng", "expert_knowledge": "# Fuzzing Build Log Analysis Expert Knowledge\n\n## General Principles for Analyzing Fuzzing Build Failures\n\n1. **Build Stage Identification**: First determine which stage of the build failed:\n   - Docker image building (dependency installation)\n   - Configuration (configure/cmake)\n   - Compilation (make/gcc/clang errors)\n   - Linking (undefined references)\n   - Fuzzer target generation\n\n2. **Error Pattern Recognition**: Common patterns include:\n   - Network issues during git clone/apt-get (retry or mirror)\n   - Missing dependencies (add packages to Dockerfile)\n   - Compiler flags incompatible with sanitizers\n   - Architecture-specific issues (x86_64 vs arm64)\n   - Header file conflicts or missing includes\n   - ABI incompatibilities between libraries\n\n3. **Dependency Resolution Strategy**:\n   - Check if all submodules are initialized\n   - Verify repository URLs are accessible\n   - Consider using pre-downloaded archives instead of git clone\n   - Add retry logic for network operations\n   - Use alternative mirrors for common dependencies\n\n4. **Sanitizer-Specific Issues**:\n   - AddressSanitizer: May conflict with certain memory allocators\n   - UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer: May trigger on legitimate code\n   - MemorySanitizer: Requires complete initialization\n   - ThreadSanitizer: May have performance implications\n\n## Pattern-Based Advice from Build Log Analysis\n\n### Pattern 1: Network/Connectivity Issues During Docker Build\n**Symptoms**: `gnutls_handshake() failed`, `The TLS connection was non-properly terminated`, timeout during git clone\n**Root Cause**: Network instability, GitHub rate limiting, or TLS library issues\n**Solutions**:\n1. Add retry logic: `RUN git clone --depth 1 URL || git clone --depth 1 URL`\n2. Use alternative protocols: Change `https://` to `git://` or use SSH\n3. Pre-download dependencies: Use `ADD` with tar.gz instead of `git clone`\n4. Increase timeout: Set `GIT_HTTP_LOW_SPEED_LIMIT` and `GIT_HTTP_LOW_SPEED_TIME`\n5. Use local mirror: If available in the base image\n\n### Pattern 2: Missing or Undeclared Identifiers in Compilation\n**Symptoms**: `error: use of undeclared identifier 'X'`, `'X' was not declared in this scope`\n**Root Cause**: Missing header includes, incorrect namespace, or conditional compilation\n**Solutions**:\n1. Check if the identifier is defined in a header that needs to be included\n2. Verify the identifier exists in the correct namespace\n3. Check for conditional compilation flags (`#ifdef`) that might exclude the definition\n4. Look for recent changes that might have renamed or moved the identifier\n5. Check for missing dependencies that provide the declaration\n\n### Pattern 3: Dockerfile Configuration Issues\n**Symptoms**: Build fails at early Docker stages, missing packages, path issues\n**Root Cause**: Incorrect Dockerfile instructions or base image problems\n**Solutions**:\n1. Verify base image digest is correct and accessible\n2. Check package names and availability in the base repository\n3. Ensure WORKDIR paths exist and are correctly set\n4. Check for multi-stage build issues\n5. Verify environment variables are properly set\n\n### Pattern 4: Regression from Compilation Error to Earlier Stage Failure\n**Symptoms**: Original error was compilation, now failing at dependency download\n**Root Cause**: Attempted fix introduced new issues or network environment changed\n**Solutions**:\n1. Don't fix what wasn't broken - address the original compilation error first\n2. Ensure network fixes don't break the build process\n3. Test network operations independently before modifying build\n4. Consider if the issue is environmental vs. code-related\n\n## Specific Advice for ntopng/nDPI Build\n\nBased on the observed patterns:\n\n1. **Current Issue**: Network failure cloning nDPI repository\n   - This is preventing the build from reaching the compilation stage\n   - The original error (undeclared `udp` in `src/Flow.cpp`) is in ntopng code, not nDPI\n   - Need to resolve network issue first, then address compilation error\n\n2. **Recommended Approach**:\n   - Fix the git clone issue in Dockerfile (add retry, use alternative URL)\n   - Once dependencies are fetched, then debug the `udp` compilation error\n   - The `udp` error suggests missing header or namespace issue in ntopng code\n\n3. **Potential Quick Fixes**:\n   ```dockerfile\n   # Instead of: RUN git clone https://github.com/ntop/nDPI.git nDPI\n   # Try: RUN git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/ntop/nDPI.git nDPI || \\\n   #          git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/ntop/nDPI.git nDPI\n   # Or: ADD https://github.com/ntop/nDPI/archive/REF.tar.gz /tmp/nDPI.tar.gz\n   #     RUN tar -xzf /tmp/nDPI.tar.gz && mv nDPI-* nDPI\n   ```\n\n4. **Compilation Error Investigation**:\n   - Once build reaches compilation stage, examine `src/Flow.cpp`\n   - Check if `udp` is a local variable, member variable, or global\n   - Look for missing `#include` statements\n   - Check if `udp` was renamed or moved in recent commits\n\n## Actionable Recommendations\n\n1. **Immediate Action**: Fix Dockerfile network issue with retry logic\n2. **Secondary Action**: Once build compiles, address `udp` declaration issue\n3. **Verification**: Test that fix doesn't break other parts of the build\n4. **Documentation**: Note the two separate issues (network + compilation) and their solutions\n\nRemember: Network issues are environmental, compilation issues are code-related. Address them separately and in the correct order."})
